Appendix A Turning Movement Count & Approach Count
CTS Engineering, Inc. was retained by FDOT and T.Y.LIN International Group to collect traffic
data along Oakland Park Boulevard in Broward County from Sawgrass Expressway to SR‐A1A as
part of the Oakland Park Boulevard PD&E study. The study corridor of Oakland Park Boulevard
is an east‐west divided roadway with 6‐lane from Sawgrass Expressway to Bayview Drive, 4‐lane
from Bayview Drive to SR‐A1A. The total length is approximately 13.3 miles.
The traffic data collection was performed on a typical weekday (e.g., Tuesday, Wednesday, and
Thursday) along Oakland Park Boulevard during the AM peak hours (7:00‐10:00 AM) and during
the PM peak hours (4:00‐7:00 PM). The data was collected during the peak season in February
The data collection entails 14 intersection Turning Movement Counts (TMCs) and 24‐Hour

intersections for TMCs and mechanical counts were chosen based on roadway functional
classification and traffic volumes. Table 1 reflects the signalized intersections that were

The Travel Time and Delay data was collected on a typical weekday (Tuesday, Wednesday and
Thursday) for each outside lane, center lane, and inside lane of eastbound and westbound
along Oakland Park Boulevard during the AM peak hour (7:00‐9:00 AM) and during the PM peak
hour (4:00‐6:00 PM). The data was collected during the peak season in April 2012 using a
floating vehicle traveling in the center lane to resemble the flow of traffic. It should be noted
that the study limit for center lane and inside lane is from Sawgrass Expressway to SR‐A1A.
However, it is from Sawgrass Expressway to Bayview Drive for Outside.

After processing the turning movement counts and the 24hr classification counts, the data was
reviewed for accuracy based on the FDOT procedures. The TMCs between adjacent
intersections were checked to see that the approaching and departing movements balanced.
When the intersections are located far from each other, the TMCs may not balance exactly due
to major attractions or driveways. Additionally, the TMCs were checked against the 24hr
approach/departure classification counts. The data was made sure that the differences in the
TMCs or the classifications counts were within the tolerance percentages (+/‐16%).
